### 1. Brief Summary of the Facts  
The case involves three appeals concerning the right of abode in Hong Kong under the Basic Law of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR). The applicants—Ng Ka Ling, Ng Tan Tan (sisters), Tsui Kuen Nang, and Cheung Lai Wah—are Chinese nationals born on the mainland to fathers who were Hong Kong permanent residents (meeting the criteria of Article 24(2)(2) of the Basic Law). They arrived in Hong Kong on or before 1 July 1997 (the handover day) and claimed the right of abode under Article 24(2)(3), which grants permanent resident status to persons of Chinese nationality born outside Hong Kong to permanent residents. The Director of Immigration (Director) denied their right of abode, requiring them to obtain a "one way permit" from mainland authorities affixed with a "certificate of entitlement" under the Immigration (Amendment) (No 3) Ordinance 1997 (No 3 Ordinance). The applicants challenged this requirement as unconstitutional, arguing their right of abode under Article 24(3) should be automatic. Cheung Lai Wah’s claim was further contested on the grounds that she was born out of wedlock, which the Director argued disqualified her under the Immigration Ordinance’s definition of parent-child relationships.  

---

### 2. Summary of the Arguments of the Two Parties  
**Applicants’ Arguments:**  
- The right of abode under Article 24(3) is absolute and unqualified by Article 22(4) (which governs entry from mainland China). Permanent residents are not "people from other parts of China" under Article 22(4), as they are already residents of Hong Kong.  
- The No 3 Ordinance’s requirement for a "one way permit" to establish permanent resident status is unconstitutional, as it strips the constitutional right of abode.  
- The retrospective application of the No 3 Ordinance (deemed effective from 1 July 1997) violates Article 15(1) of the International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights (ICCPR), as it would retroactively criminalize their lawful presence in Hong Kong.  
- The Immigration Ordinance’s provision excluding children born out of wedlock from father-child relationships (para 1(2)(b)) is unconstitutional, violating equality principles under the ICCPR and the Basic Law.  

**Director’s Arguments:**  
- Article 22(4) qualifies the right of abode in Article 24(3), requiring mainland residents (including those claiming permanent resident status) to obtain mainland approval (via a "one way permit") for entry.  
- The No 3 Ordinance’s scheme (requiring a certificate of entitlement affixed to a one way permit) is constitutional, as it implements Article 22(4) and aligns with the Joint Declaration’s "present practice" of regulating entry.  
- The birth out of wedlock issue disqualifies Cheung Lai Wah, as the Immigration Ordinance treats fathers differently from mothers for illegitimate children.  
- The Provisional Legislative Council (PLC), which enacted the No 3 Ordinance, was legally constituted under the 1990 Decision of the National People’s Congress, rendering the Ordinance valid.  

